caption: This is the best cajun food and I love the  ambience! This place is special.
Perfect place for get together party !
Upscale seafood eating. Excellent steaks as well. Try their amazing carrot cake to finalize a wonderful meal.

I have visited this spot many times, and I just love it. We went the last time the weekend of Mardi Gras, and had a blast. It was crowded, but worth it. The food here is always amazing, but that weekend they put on a show. The atmosphere was lively. They had a love jazz band, and the owner was there as the king of Mardi Gras, it was so much fun. This will always be one of my favorite spots in Chicago. How can you not love Heaven on Seven? It's amazing.

Ate at Heaven on Seven during a short weekend trip last week. It was great! I had the Jambalaya and it was cooked perfectly. Generous portions, but not so big that it can't be finished. Just enough to have you leaving full and satisfied. Fair prices as well. The restaurant has no less than 1000+ different hot sauces from around the world, and our server was somewhat of a "Hot sauce sommelier" he was able to make excellent sauce recommendations for every stage of our meal.
Love this place, sorry that they're closed during the pandemic, but will be there as soon as they reopen!

A top place for delicious cajun food. Service is always timely even when they have a full house. Definitely worth going back to. Bring your hunger - portions are large. Menu is similar to a restaurant in El Paso I loved.

Outstanding place to eat. I would put it up against any restaurant in New Orleans, it's that good. When in Chicago we never leave town without eating there and even once traveling to Naperville because it happened to be a Sunday and the Chicago location was closed on that day. Keep it up Jimmy!
This place was great. Loved all the decorations and the food was good. Definitely try to get there closer to 11 for lunch though because it was very busy.

We came for lunch on a break during a conference at the Palmer House. It was a short walk. The restaurant itself is on the 7th floor of a building and it is small and becomes quite crowded during lunch hours. We were able to be seated fairly quickly for a group of 6. Poboys were enjoyed by others at the table as well as gumbo. I ordered the red beans and rice, which was good, but didn't have much andouille in it. I would probably order a poboy next time instead. Several bottles of hot sauce were available at the table, which was neat. We love New Orleans and Cajun food, so it was nice to have something close to authentic this far north.
My family in NOLA would be PROUD.

The Cajun food is excellent, service fun and attentive and a unique establishment with lots of character! We enjoyed the Jambalya, Gumbo soup and all of the suggested spicy sauces to try - whew - can't wait to go back!!!

If you ask nicely for a hot sauce cup, you can mix your hot sauces. (Some people even drink it.) if you are looking for a lively, fun time in the city, this is the place to go.

As fate would have it I was looking for someplace good to eat and when I looked at the GPS what did I know, Heaven on Seven was less than 0.5 miles away from my current location. Although it's been awhile the food and the service have not changed. It was like visiting an old friend's house I felt right at home. The atmosphere and the service was impeccable. Despite its description, this place makes for a great dinner location. It can be difficult to find, being on the 7th floor, but getting there is worth it. It is a uniquely-decorated restaurant whose fried fish that melts in your mouth. Their coleslaw is also very good, but I found their gumbo or beans and rice side to be a less flavorful than expected. Service here was also exceptional.

Heaven on 7 is an amazing hidden gem that you look very cool taking people to. Nestled down a hallway on the 7th floor of an office building is some of the best Cajun food you can find in the Midwest. Try the gumbo, peacemaker poor boy, daily etoufee, and the shrimp and grits.

Amazing spicy Southern food! They even offer a Siracha infused drink - which is not for the faint hearted! Great cozy atmosphere with walls full of hot sauces. It's a bit hard to find (on 7th floor) but absolutely worth it.
Shh. It's Chicago's best kept Creole secret. For years this food has delighted the palates of those in the know. Get there. Do not skip the gumbo.
What a gem. This place was recommended to me by a friend. It has a lot of character and the food was delicious. Be prepared to taste some new flavours and soak up the atmosphere.

We found Heaven on Seven years ago on our very first visit to Chicago and it is a "must eat here" on every return trip. I'm embarrassed to admit that every single time I've been here, prior to today, I ordered a Shrimp Po Boy. Geez, I have really missed out on all kinds of deliciousness. Today, I had the creamiest grits  I have ever eaten. And collard greens? I could've made a meal of them--slightly sweetened,  they were tender and well cooked. And I finally had dessert. Chocolate Peanut Butter Pie. It's called a pie but the texture is a cross between a cheesecake and a smooth fudge and has immediately become the standard which I will judge every other peanut butter pie I have in the future. I always encourage people to eat here when in Chicago. Having traveled extensively in the South, I believe Heaven  on Seven serves some of the best Creole/Cajun food this side of New Orleans. Today's visit just reaffirmed that opinion.

We went there on Tuesday for a late lunch.  No wait got right in.  It was a cold rainy day so we craved for hot gumbo.  It was located on the seventh floor in a business-looking building so we would’ve never expected there is a restaurant in the middle floor.  We had to ask around where the restaurant is located and then we learned that we need to take the elevator up to 7th floor.  Ambience is pretty cool.  Southern decor resembling Louisiana I assume.  Service was outstanding.  We had some questions on the menu and the server was friendly and explained all the questions we had.  A lot of seasonings on the table for your customizable experience.  We ordered the famous Nashville hot chicken, jalapeno corn muffin, and a bowl of gumbo.  The chicken dish was really hot and the muffin helped a lot.  The hot chicken was not on the regular menu, it was written on the board on the wall as house specials.  We were full after the chicken and the gumbo, could not finish the muffin and the fries all the way.  Two of us paid $29.80 after tax.  Very reasonable price for the quality food.  Highly recommended.
Gumbo was great!  The server was polite and  Accommodating

Absolutely solid cajun food. Located on the seventh floor of an office building; go through the lobby of the Garland Building and take a normal office elevator to the seventh floor. Can get crowded at lunch. CASH ONLY. ATM available. You should order the cajun food, and you should opt for the gumbo that comes as a first course with most of the regular meals. Desserts are enormous and should be shared. They are also on some of the online delivery / ordering services. Catering is available for large groups and is recommended; the food travels well. Always ask about the specials; there is always an etouffee of the day and it is always good.
